ndividual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and wha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t gaps there are in support for schools at this level.”</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academy schools are required through their funding agreement to comply with admissions law as it applies to maintained schools.  Amendments to the Act made by the Education Act 2011 gave the power to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Adjudicator to rule on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">objections to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">admission arrangements for academy schools.  Previously</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the power to make a determination</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">objections to the arrangements for academy schools rested with the Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  The EFA acting for the Secretary o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f State was able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seek the views of the adjudicator before making a decision.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  In 2011 and up to 1 February 2012 the EFA requested a recommendation for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> objections it had received.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The change in legislation so that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all objections to admission arrange</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> determined by the Adjudicator has enabled those who wish to object to know that whatever the type of school, all objections are dealt with by a single body</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> using the same procedures for all schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The OSA receives many enquiries </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of which a significant number concern matters that are outside its remit.  Some of these include queries about seeking a variation to an academy school’s arrangements and making a direction of a child to a school.  The differences in the process for academ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y and maintained schools can result in delays while the enquirer is redirected to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">EFA as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relevant body.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The queries concerning directions to an academy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have reduced following the Department for Education’s guidance,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> “Fair Access Protocols: P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rinciples and Process”,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> issued in November 2012.  However, there are still cases that are referred to the OSA concerning a maintained school where the directing local authority has not followed the correct process for making a direction </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to a maintained sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ool </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as set out in the Act which results in a child being out of school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for longer than is necessary.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  While the process for making a direction to an academy school has been clarified there have been more cases received by the OSA where the different proces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s for a maintained school has not met the terms set by the Act and thus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">delays occur in placing the child.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There may be some merit in looking at the differences, small though they are, between the process to be followed for maintained schoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and academy school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in respect of variations to determined admission arrangements and the final sanction for finding a school place for a child through making a direction to admit.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Then consider the pros and cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of having different requirements and deci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sion makers for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maintained and academy schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, especially whether it is the most efficient way of proceeding when the process for considering objections to admission arrangemen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ts of all schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">within one body, the OSA.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Chief Adjudi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cator is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">required to prepare an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> annual report to the Secretary of State that reports on the work of the OSA and gives a summary of the report from local authorities to the Adjudicator.  The most recent report was published on 29 November 2013 and can be found at </span><a href="C:\Users\mcelweec\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Content.IE5\JSFI3F6A\www.education.gov.uk\schoolsadjudicator\about"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.education.gov.uk/schoolsadjudicator/about</span></a><a name="_GoBack"></a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The fourth main finding is, “New schools and those that become their own admission authority do not always fully understand their responsibilities for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> having lawful admission arrangements that comply fully with admission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> law and the Code”.  The action required is recorded as, “The Department for Education should ensure that there is clear guidance for new schools and those that change their status to b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecome their own admission authority about the requirements and the timetable to be followed concerning admissions matters”. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many of the school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that have become an academy school were previously their own admission authority as a foundation or voluntary a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ided school.  This does not mean that they all have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> had </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arrangements that comply with the Code, but at least they have some understanding of what is required.  For schools that were community or voluntary controlled the local authority was the admission au</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thority so the change of status bri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the new responsibility for admissions.  Completely new schools, such as free schools, need to ensure that they are fully alert to what they have to do by specified dates and they need to be certain they have lawfully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">determined admission arrangements.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  I anticipate that the Department will provide further guidance for schools, new and existing ones, that become their own admission authority. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>